The Prague Stock Exchange is falling to a minus.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
The transactions with the ČEZ shares reached almost half of the normal day trading.
The Prague stock exchange closely linked to Monday’s crash at the start of Tuesday’s trading, when it fell by another six percentage points.
This time it was the cause of the Wall Street collapse.
In the Czech Republic, too, the markets reacted to the result of the vote of the U.S. House of Representatives, which refused to support a stabilization plan for the financial sector there.
Falling stocks in Asia
The stock markets in Asia experienced a dramatic drop on Tuesday, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hang Seng Hong Kong stock exchange index lost four percentage points over the course of the business day, but was later able to offset part of the losses, thus reducing the drop to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while the markets in Shanghai were closed.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange fell by 3.6 percent following the index there.
“The timing of the rescue operation in the United States is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide,” said the head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority, Joseph Yam.
Although Hong Kong belongs to China, it determines its own monetary policy, thus independent of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and pass the draft for supporting the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries would also be affected by the robbery.
A bloodshed of American stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which would cost up to $700 billion (nearly 12 trillion Kčs).
Thus, lawmakers ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the underlying causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodshed on Monday, and major stock indices recorded the biggest fall in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by seven percent, the last time it had recorded a similar drop was in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there were hardly any signs that the draft would not pass through the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress gives concessions: U.S. government can pump $700 billion into banks
The top representatives of the U.S. Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
This will be voted at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a breakthrough in negotiations on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of a $700 billion ($12 trillion) financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
However, this does not mean a victory.
Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish the final draft of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the US Congress on Monday.
This was stated by Barney Frank, Chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services, to Reuters.
In the Senate, according to various reports, the plan could probably be voted at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the plan will be adopted should be the first significant psychological factor in revitalizing the financial markets.
After that, however, there is a “indignation” due to the complicated mechanisms of helping the markets in practice.
The plan must be effective.
“We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our divergent views on what a package to stabilize the market should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to him, a final vote could be held on Sunday.
Representatives of the lawmakers met on Sunday night with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give the government fund its final shape.
It provides for the purchase of non-selling mortgage assets from financial companies, which plunges the financial firms into heavy losses and endangers the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We need to continue the recovery plan even further, but I think we are at our goal,” Paulson said.
A Signal for Asian Business
The global financial crisis has also significantly impacted the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid of Nevada, lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress before Sunday.
It is aimed at reassuring investors against transactions in Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a congressional decision could affect Monday’s transactions.
However, it is not yet clear when both houses of the U.S. Congress will vote on the law, and there is uncertainty as to whether the last-minute negotiations could not fail on a problem.
Legislators hope it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will undergo some changes.
The total amount allocated to support the system shall be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion will be allocated as soon as possible, as President George Bush called for.
But Congress can block the distribution of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, with another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush positive on progress in negotiations
The President has a veto right, but Congress can veto it.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was based on obtaining funding for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages, has remained.
“We have prepared everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday, then the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President Bush was also pleased with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday’s progress and “appreciates the bilateral efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Reduction of gold parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, concluding benefits and a timetable for funding the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and to set up a committee to oversee the fund.
This is to be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on it and made great progress towards a deal that works and is important for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also expects to provide assistance to homeowners who have trouble paying off their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new rates on mortgages it buys, with the goal of reducing monthly costs for debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological assistance
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but implementation will be very difficult.
“And that’s because you don’t know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be purchased.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government will share the losses,” Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or early next week, according to Marek, is not decisive.
“More importantly, congressmen agree to support the plan and pass it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement that there will be an adoption is the most important thing at this time," Marek stressed.
Duel on knife cutting: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you in your choice.
While almost every phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can still make phone calls.
Therefore, of course, it seems that it is better to buy just one phone.
There are many reasons why you should choose an independent player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the requirements of the future owner.
Certainly it is hard to buy a great, expensive record player at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
Once such musical innovations do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view, there is also no objective reason for this.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you’re probably dreaming of at least one.
This is also the case with music on travel, i.e. with compressed music, in simple terms - music in MP3 format.
There are also price and quality categories.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but also a Pink Floyd fan will hardly get headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
The life of the batteries is also important.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what phones can do, they don’t even do implicitly.
No modern device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary features, calling and simming, it can play music and videos, record both, it has a better, a worse camera, and maybe it can also navigate.
And if you still include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill or take pictures of a TV.
However, the universality of mobile phones also has disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to charge it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy-eaters.
Few phones can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, most of it is much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
This is why you should expect that the cheap phones will not be able to play music for more than a few hours.
If you still call the phone from time to time, buy a charger for the office for security – this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have this problem, even the less good will keep at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation with one-time charging out.
Another problem is when you want to play the music on your phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices have a USB port, and not every phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can play the music directly onto a storage medium, but few card readers do without reduction with the tiny memory cards used in phones.
For players, you do not need any special software except for exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device via USB port with music from your PC.
Most phones and players set up a music library by themselves, sorted by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre, or, for example, user ratings.
Some devices only represent the tree structure of the address directory, similar to the Windows Explorer, some can both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should ask in particular about the life of the battery, the storage capacity, the quality and type of sound and, of course, also the comfort of operation.
If for you music is primarily background and you only listen to it for a short time every day, for example in the tram, then any phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
Almost every cell phone can do this.
You also don’t have to control what music formats a phone or player can process.
MP3 creates all, and most of the music you get will be just in that format.
The format is one of the most common, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better phones also allow you to buy music online.
You only need to access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via the mobile internet, and you can already purchase a song or album.
This service can in itself be a striking argument for why you should wear a music phone.
Unfortunately, the provider’s offer is poor and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
Prices are not the lowest.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of sales of music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people wear the cell phone with them.
If you want to listen to something, grab the phone in your pocket while the player is at home.
However, it depends whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless free speaker device with you.
If not, you can resort to the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be in the price for many.
The cheapest usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you get a very decent Walkman.
The biggest disadvantage for most will be that there are no normal headphones with them.
The best and most technically sophisticated phones with a 3.5mm aperture for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players, in turn, lies in the easy operation.
The easiest - and not necessarily the cheapest (see selection) - player can really serve anyone.
A minimum of features, the similarity in operation with the previously normal cassette recorder or, for example, the disc player is obvious.
There is no threat of collision in the form of a mistakenly employed mobile Internet and a subsequent horrifying bill for data transfers.
Which device should you use
Even the cheapest phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns will be enough.
But attention though.
Basic models typically only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can also read 8-GB memory cards.
If you already own a phone and still want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, then resort to Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
Belonging to the more demanding listeners, prefer to take specialized phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3, and the convenience of use is similar to that of a single MP3 player.
The most extensive is Sony Ericsson, whose phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours) will afford you MP3 players of the above-mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic to lower prices.
Maybe it won’t wait long anymore.
That the Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often on Mobil.cz.
This, by the way, was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which drew attention to the fact that the price for a SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the recent steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, it is likely to come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile operator, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really makes a fight.
Per it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to cheat about the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
This is often attributed to Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (by the way, he would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market that brought with it a significant price reduction, to which then also the classic mobile providers had to react.
Even before the entry of companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices in the UK as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
You do not have to look for examples for long.
In February this year we about the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the country’s fifth largest provider.
Mobilking is backed by the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
They do not require relatively high costs for building, operating andining a mobile network.
In the world, the virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less comprehensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-cliché target audience.
This service is specifically aimed at men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the provider of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept could take place in the Czech Republic as in Poland.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesman for Vodafone, said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic, there is no chance, say mobile providers
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobilking.
"While we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look hopeful.
It is likely that Mobilking will enter the market in other countries in our region,” says Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
She indirectly confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
GTS Novera Group has long demonstrated its interest in launching a virtual mobile operator, which aims to take another step towards becoming a real competitor to Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
The sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming.
Non-official information suggests that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
Until now, however, this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
“At the moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has significant differences compared to other markets.
So far, no entity has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area,” said Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds, in rare accord with O2’s statement: “So far we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on.”
And she adds: "There will hardly be a single virtual provider on T-Mobile's network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete offer in place to be able to think so short-term.”
Vodafone is focusing more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the best from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for high-speed mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities – hand in hand with providers
The behavior of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also a decrease in profits.
So why should we make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
That the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something, also proves the long way around the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ came from the company T-Mobile at the time U:fon came on the market.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
U:fon is a good argument for why you shouldn’t allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová said: “The competitive environment in the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile provider.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would put high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services.”
However, given this approach by the mobile operators, it is surprising that the Czech regulatory authorities are completely disinterested.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which in the Czech Republic unfortunately – unlike the UK and other highly developed countries – does not have the competence to interfere in economic competition.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, referred to his very typical attitude to this whole problem.
The entry of a virtual mobile operator into the market would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for the traditional providers,” said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of Foreign Relations of the ÚOHS in his response to our request.
Representatives of the providers would not be surprised by such a formulation.
From an authority that represents consumer interests and is intended, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses his position in the market, this is more than worrying.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: “In foreign countries, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services.”
Probably, however, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not in the interests of the ÚOHS.
Really shocking in this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile providers resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the exact same price of gasoline at the gas stations is surely just a coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
The Authority has not found any signs of anti-competitive action in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the providers have a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions in the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market to virtual providers are likely to be lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view – for the entry into the market of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has, logically, the monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
But even if you do not follow this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting strikingly similarly.
Complaints from a number of stakeholders (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles in negotiating with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to enforce the extension of the competences of the ČTÚ to the field of economic competition in telecommunications in the recently adopted novel of the Telecommunications Act, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It happens when no one looks.
The functioning of any pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, is not taken into account.
These are companies that issue their own pricing lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partially public.
These are usually companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach selected people.
The joke of the thing is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer ordering a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile providers prohibit similar type of resale.
"If there are cases you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual terms, which we will then deal with, which can lead to the termination of cooperation with the corresponding company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is unlikely that such a thing will not happen with the responsibility of the mobile providers.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such action.
In fact, these companies do not generate negligible profits from their activities, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points to possible problems: “The law allows for such kinds of speculation, despite all, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not running on their name, so they can’t have it as fully as the normal customers of the mobile operators.”
That alone, however, should at least seem strange to the ČTÚ.
Also, another question opens up for the UOHS.
When mobile providers close their eyes to such actions, why do they lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to satisfy itself with the declaration of the providers that they would know nothing about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasized several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers led to a significant decline in the prices of the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence.
The arguments they used were virtually identical – a too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, it was at these moments that regulators intervened, trying not to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that uncertainty in competencies in these cases is more than favourable.
But let us not throw the flies into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon appears, the Czech mobile market may soon be moving again.
If a provider permits the emergence of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And then the Czechs will finally not pay more than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Find the best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech National Anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Where is my homeland.
The hymn was recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo singing, in choir and in an instrumental version.
The song was composed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions at once.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech National Anthem is one of the most beautiful hymns.
Earlier, he told the Czech broadcaster that he has selected singers with young, representative voices that are prominent and popular for the solo variants.
"From the beginning, I tried to keep a clear diction with both and then with the choir, so that you can understand the text well, so that there is harmony," said the conductor.
The Czech National Anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj first sounded on the stage of the Ständetheater in 1834 in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music came from František Škroup.
It became popular, and people took it spontaneously.
The first strip of the song became an organic part of the national anthem after the formation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
