The Prague transport companies will be transporting on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will enter the history of Prague transport operations as a date when the first passengers board a subway, tram or bus carrying an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently be purchased by about one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and play it on their chip card at the same time at the information centers and branches of the transport operators at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons are also available on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon.
Those who use internet sales can really forget the output window in the metro stations, where they had to regularly wait in long queues for their paper carts.
You buy the coupon via the Internet and play it on the Opencard at one of the 13 branches of the city library.
“At these points, travellers also have a switch with trained staff who advises interested parties on online shopping and also plays the coupon on the card,” said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on self-service machines on the opencard, which are mounted in some subway vestibules.
How do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket designers, the passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"At the moment there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there are eighty," Opatrný adds.
The coupon is controlled by an automaton instead of the driver
Operating the machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
All you have to do is enter the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon will play off on its own.
The electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which mostly the inhabitants from municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia get to the capital.
"In the trains that are part of Prague's integrated traffic, the train attendants have readers that allow them to check the validity period of the coupons by time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization's ticket control.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver’s box.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be presented to the driver, but the open card must be placed in a marked place on the side of the box.
This allows the driver to check the validity of the recorded coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the recorded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal said.
A passenger who does not travel with suburban buses and no longer knows when the coupon expires can, in turn, go to the self-service machines, where the coupons are played on the card.
Here, the information about the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
Sudans Call for U.S. Referendum
In 1945, the Sudet Germans requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States.
This is stated in a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudet Germans appealed to the President of the United States.
This is evidenced, among other things, in a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau in the letter ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengaus" - which was taken on the basis of the Munich agreement by Hitler - to Czechoslovakia.
“We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure that the American units are not entering German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” the letter says, which is signed with the words “people who care about the fate of the Sudets.”
As the annexation of Czechoslovakia leads the Sudeten Germans, aware of the Czech national character, to suspect that they would expect brutality, recklessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the patronage of the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the views of a quarter-million inhabitants of this territory, you are speaking to a state foreign to us, which has sought to oppress and eliminate minorities and has not contributed at all to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors can’t sign is supposedly the fear of revenge cravings of the “Czech oppressors.”
If the U.S. President had doubts about the attitude of the Bohemians, it would be sufficient for him to initiate a referendum in Bohemians about whether the inhabitants would become part of the United States or live under the protectionism of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today's knowledge of post-war history, however, according to some contemporary witnesses, it draws a good picture with regard to the expectations of the Sudet Germans at the time.
Although the Bohemian Germans at least had to suspect that their deportation from the republic would be negotiated, few of them realized such a possibility at all.
Some expected the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudets.
Others thought they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
During the war he served as a Budweiser German in the Baltic Sea Navy.
When he came into British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that when they came home, they would be happy with the Czech language," Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners of war who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected, in his opinion, that he would be expelled from the republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
