Even rats have feelings.
If a rat or a frog escapes in danger, does that mean that it also feels fear?
The neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have emotions.
Just how can we check if they feel the same when they behave like us?
The Internet magazine "Edge" has published contributions from famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having been able to prove this so far where we can not even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and cut off issues of sensation or consciousness in general, we enter unmovable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as many other animals: it stands dead, flees, or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, which some scientists conclude with a comparable subjective experience.
I do not believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This wide region is much more developed in humans than in the rest of the primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So at least with those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that humans are even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since such a large part of his experience is associated with speech, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how composed it may be, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor analyzed, because of the special hardware, based on our own experience, then its research poses us great problems.
Most of my arguments relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that is more scientifically accessible.
One could study the consciousness processes of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies of primate short-term memory, especially in the example of visualization.
But this approach, followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, relies more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the state of visualization.
What happens to the sensations?
I bring them back to the fact that an emotional system such as fear is activated in one of its own activity-conscious brains.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) demonstrates working memory.
Thus, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and in particular humans.
In conjunction with the linguistic nature, there are fine grades of sensation, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations arise from more primitive activities in the body sensory regions of the cortex and brain stem, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network hasn’t changed much in the course of human evolution, it might well be involved in cross-genre sensations.
Theoretically, I cannot contradict this, but I find it unproven.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans probably feels like it in both cases: but how can one check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
Does a cow run away in danger if she feels afraid too?
In my view, mere similarity of behavior cannot yet prove experiential equality.
Although the neural comparison helps further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, frogs do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it to humans, how could you prove it to rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even frogs (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don’t know how to prove that.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I’d rather explore the emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, there is progress at the neural level here, as long as the same is measured in rats and humans.
Just as I do not study language and consciousness in rats, nor sensations, I do not know if they exist.
You may think it’s short-sighted, but I’d rather move forward than constantly run against a wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
