Debate on bilingual education: education in an English-speaking environment
In this issue of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior researcher in California Studies and senior director of education sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book “Not as good as one thinks: Why the middle class needs a school choice.”
Addressing the Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s campaign mentioned that “the probability of African-American and Hispanic students successfully finishing school is lower than that of white students” – which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s educational plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transitional phase in education for those first to learn English.
Still, the question to Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take for example Sixth Street Prep, a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than one-third of the students, many of whom have recently been in the country, are learning English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, amazing 100 percent of fourth-grade students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of fourth-year schoolchildren scored well on the English test.
This amazing success has been achieved with methods other than those preferred by Obama.
The Sixth Street School places its emphasis on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that does not tolerate exceptions.
Furthermore, the school practices the approach by which education is conducted in an English-speaking environment.This is exactly the point that Obama should consider, said school director Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialized teaching.
Mrs Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school would have a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico.
“It works,” she noted, “it works for us.”
Would Obama take a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a high percentage of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school’s achievements would make it easy to answer this question, but the educational positions within his own party (the national educational associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s response uncertain.
While agreeing on the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the topic by noting that people should stop worrying about legislation aiming at “only English.”
Instead, he said, “You should make sure your child can speak Spanish.”
If Obama really wants to close the gap in performance, he should carefully consider educational models that work, rather than despise and trivialize them.
