Haile Gebrselassie from Ethiopia has once again shown why he is considered by some to be the best long-distance runner of all time, after breaking his own record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to complete the 42.2 km track in less than 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the victory on the flat course at 2:03:59, Gebrselassie has improved his previous score of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved last year in Berlin.
Brzselassie, 35, has thus set his 26th world record in his diverse career, in which he has achieved at least one world championship title or set a world record on every track from one kilometer to the marathon.
Last month, Brzselassie missed the Olympic Marathon in Beijing, fearing that air pollution could worsen his asthma problems.
Instead, he signed up for the competition in Berlin.
In almost ideal conditions – with sunshine and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish – Gebrselassie has won at an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since runner-ups like Brzselassie and Paul Tergat from Kenya have switched on long distances, the record time for marathon in the last 10 years has fallen by more than 2 minutes since Ronaldo da Costa of Brazil won in Berlin in 1998 with the result 2:06:05.
