The pride and hardships in the lives of the black people, in a city of a very special kind.
Hidden among the groves of the amusement parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic drift, a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first entirely black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurstons, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: “the city with 5 lakes, three cricket courses, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guaven, 2 schools, and no prison.”
Today it is a pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous Harlem Renaissance writer.
And yet the city it describes – and which made it a tourist destination by bringing it to the Florida Travel Guide produced by the Federal Writers Project during the times of depression – is and remains in many ways a place of a very special sort.
Eatonville is as independent, thriving and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t know what’s missing him.”
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation about racial relationships, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
“We are very concerned about how our story is told,” says Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and a member of the congregation of the city’s oldest church.
It has to vote.”
Eatonville has long been defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historic example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants where the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural south, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and vigilant.
And so rightly, concerns about Eatonville’s image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in the mouth, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973)
Five passages in the Florida guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Like Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville’s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Beyond the street to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white-painted modern school, with its well-maintained gardens and playgrounds, which is always taken care of by Howard Miller, though he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and anything-even-always fits into classrooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait appreciated by everyone.
"Zora described things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls Hurston immortalized by quoting the men singing songs about their beauty that were full of sexual suggestions.
She added, “Some people didn’t like this.”
Here, Hurtson is still remembered as a vibrant eccentric who regularly returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came into the city, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in pants, in a city that even today imagines something of her respectable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most residents were fascinated, while many despised them.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” said Mr. Franklin.
But “she never stayed too long,” he added as he swung in his chair, on a rear-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was probably baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were wasted.
Together with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous writer, a contemporary of Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no big commemoration, no public reading in a big style.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Wrapped in Rainbows, a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to build a five-track highway through the city to replace the Kennedy Boulevard, the municipality’s slow two-track main road.
Orlando’s suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts.
The proposal was submitted as Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the struggle against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"During this time, often a bunch of white boys came and they threw oranges and stuff on the people sitting away," said Mr. Franklin.
“There was once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car.”
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court’s demand to enforce integration by describing its decision in the Brown v. School Council case as “insulting rather than respecting my race.”
Inhabitants today say that while the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some ways, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - one hugged his teacher in the morning and one hugged his teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group to protect the Eatonville community.
That could beined for so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
“You didn’t embrace your white teacher because he was a white teacher – I mean there’s a cultural gap,” Nathiri said.
However, civil rights helped make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons – black authors, actors and artists who wandered over prejudice, just as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, “How can anyone deny themselves the joy of my society!
I do not understand.”
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out on her way to Hurston's nameless tomb and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-loved Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was found on the shelves, making it once again part of the American literary canon.
The long-haul project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public light.
And this time Hurston’s old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The municipality began in 1988 planning a Hurston Festival to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many come back for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans for a five-track highway revived the city, accelerated the whole thing at peak speed, aroused real citizen pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Ms. Boyd put it a little simpler: “Zora saved Eatonville.”
The victory over the highway project has contributed to a change in the self-image of the city.
There were more and more visitors, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was included in the National Historical Register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (naturally named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a special feature in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a backyard in summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today it is 90% black.)
Outsiders looking for the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, prior approval is required, and certain things—such as the wall painting of Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in field work—are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a brave, self-confident teacher with a preference for dark red, are still afraid that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew bigger, there was also an increased degree of homeland pride.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better, and just as proud, creative and diligent, foolish and mixed as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, the 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who intends to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, which he says might need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just go through here will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said recently on a Sunday after the church.
“But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it’s a very beautiful city.”
Here in New York, we speak fluent financial Latin.
At first glance nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newspapers stands and the huge TV screens on Times Square, they’t even realize that they’re in the midst of a debacle.
They would never believe that over their heads, in the shoe-box-like offices with the glass facades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York, every day have the worst horror working day since the 1929 stock market crash.
Suppliers are still pushing the metal tea trails along the sidewalks with loud taps and carrying tablets loaded with muffins for the breakfast sessions.
Latinos are still gliding around between apartments as human packed animals load around the 50 wrapped T-shirts hanging on a yoke-like rod lying on their shoulders.
Office employees are still waiting on their own on the sidewalk dining stalls for their breakfast bagel and it’s still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 16 and 19.
It didn’t feel like a crisis at all until I decided to open a new savings account on Thursday afternoon due to all the end-of-the-world talk.
Though I had decided to set my duty on the quiet late afternoon at my JP Morgan Chase branch, there were about 20 people in line.
Not at the exchanges to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service exchanges where regular customers order checkbooks, tourists ask about the way to Macy's store, and where new customers open accounts.
Most before me, so I learned later from Starr, my “licensed personal bank worker,” stood for the same reason as I had.
Unlike me, however, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks, in places from where they moved, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (somewhat like a building fund), cooperative banks, and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state, and say they treat their customers like a family.
Last year, 15 of these banks went bankrupt quietly.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went into bankruptcy management and as New Yorkers drove home over the weekend last Friday, Wachovia, another bank with $440 billion in savings, was looking for a saving buyer.
In fear of another collapse, the office and store employees who stood in front of me brought their bars to a bank that is considered a safe haven, a bank that is responsible for most rescue purchases on Wall Street.
Very normal New Yorkers have adopted a flowing financial latitude in recent weeks.
A woman who was calling in my Chinese supermarket was referring to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank, and its faint-looking chief executive Dick Fuld with so much familiarity, as if she were blaspheming about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, who is around the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my residential block, has gone away from our usual conversation topics about Brad and Angelina and my food delivery.
"I now have all my savings in money market funds," she told me after my visit to the bank.
“I’ve changed, I don’t take any risks anymore.”
