Isabel Bayón recalls the memory of the dancer from Sevilla Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville honors a dancer who also came from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalan (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and her mother Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the district of Triana and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and an expert in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first fighters for the emancipation of women, like Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, vegetarian and advocated the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free movement of women.
The life of this woman, who left her mark in the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe in the interwar period, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
“I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this role, which seemed impossible to me.”
“We are not trying to tell about her life, but to preserve her spirit,” said the flamenco dancer.
Their dance basics helped me a lot in flamenco.
For example, “The Dance of the Butterfly” seemed to me like Guajira, or “The Dance of the Serpent” like tango.
Her dance was sensual and I’ve been told that my dance is also in this aesthetic area,” she says.
The staging expects two extraordinary collaborations: with Miguel Poveda, who will sing again for Isabel at one of her performances, as he also did in 'La puerta abierta'; and with flamenco master Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with one of her ex-students.
Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I’m happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I feel very honored.”
The stage also includes musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the singing of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the violin of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Júarez, he 'takes the role of the companion of the artists who were the divas in which he falls in love again and again.'
This work also tells in a certain way about the life of this woman, who became known in such remote places as India, the United States or Russia and also throughout Europe, although she normally lived in London.
“I wanted to recall her because I think she is one of those women who have an enormous influence on a particular epoch and whose works are no longer appreciated by anyone, and therefore even less appreciated,” Bayón said.
The show will take place at 8:30 p.m. at the Lope de Vega Theatre.
