Drivers who may fall back because of the alcohol level will have to install the ‘Alcolock’.
The authority orders that the driver, who had three official penalties for the level of alcohol, install this system in his car, which prohibits him from starting the car in a drunk state.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the Attorney General.
The purpose is the resocialization of the driver, which is why he receives a course for re-education of traffic behavior.
In addition to the Attorney General, according to experience, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for Automobile Safety will also participate.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of drivers who have been arrested more than once for driving under the influence of alcohol have re-settled in the wheel.
The ‘alcolock’ would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents car start when the driver has made a alcohol test; or when a alcohol concentration is detected that is higher than permitted.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, the costs are borne by the one who imposes the sanction.
In this context, a study conducted in the U.S. in 2007 has shown that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of rules breaches in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address that behavior before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate its implementation, a legal reform can be implemented in the usual way, and yet a reform of the basic law is required, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
Still, the device is not available in any store in the Spanish markets, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the House of Representatives will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses.
