Interview - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained public confidence, severely shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service were contaminated with the HIV and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and developing guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to deliver his report, several provinces then set up a committee to develop a new system for managing blood preserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started its work, only 38% of people had confidence in the blood preservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was disappointing.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of the blood preserves and through the work in this field over the following years, we have regained public confidence,” she says, before proudly emphasizing that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of Quebec’s population now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary remains conscious that “confidence is something extremely fragile.”
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the emergence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has held the lead since its founding in 1998.
“And we had no idea whether this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So let us refer to one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which exclusion measures are applied when one does not know it and when a disease only progresses slowly, as is evident in the case of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself by degeneration of the brain, inevitably leading to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, no blood was taken from persons who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it was proven that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the precautionary principle we applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which allow to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NSTs made it possible to shorten the incubation period that occurs between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood through our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements allowed to significantly reduce the risk of transmission of AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, this means that you would have to distribute 12 million bottles of blood before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood bottles each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood bottle occurs.
I believe that you can feel comfortable getting or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health nowadays,” says Hema-Quebec’s chief executive.
“Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted by insects through the blood.
We need to monitor continuously,” Dr. Décary continues, before emphasizing that Hema-Quebec needs to provide adequate supplies in addition to secure supplies.
“The demand increases because the population is ageing.
Because cancer treatment is more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
Population aging also affects the blood donor network, which, on average, comprises only 3% of Quebec’s eligible residents.”
Any healthy person aged 18 or older who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who donate their blood are not accepted, for example, because they have AIDS or malaria, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is widespread are excluded from donating blood for a year.
“With these 3% we are able to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but most importantly to keep them and get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that one rarely finds time to spend an hour donating blood,” regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec not only supplies preserved blood, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being interim stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec’s only public umbilical cord blood bank.
In the umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, there is blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand each year.
“We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes the program as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced they don’t have access to it because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all of Quebec’s hospitals.
