Orwell's Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, deputy general director of the Canadian gold mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms, and follows Orwell’s logic, that the world’s largest gold-mining company sought a six-million blasphemy lawsuit against three authors and a small middle-handed publishing house, with the aim of opening a “public transparent debate.”
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge on the truth, especially not in the case of defamatory lawsuits, but on the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to defend one of their opposing opinions.
No matter how the process goes, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defence and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic in these unequal battles, by the way, is often to ruin the defenders in order to impose a consensus arrangement that will make the opposing side mouthless and, in addition, discourage anyone who dares to address the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to the public.
Contrary to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada, debates are usually carried out through the exchange of ideas and not by cuddling.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened up a real debate through which newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent audit teams could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in the public opinion, wiping aside the petitions and letters supporting the authors of Noir Canada with a handshake.
Could Mr. Garver explain how he could at the same time ask for a “public” debate while ignoring the opinions of that public?
Apparently, this word in the vice president’s world only includes the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a pretty narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even blasphemers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does this mainly because it rejects the gold mine’s brutal attitude.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a jerk (during the ‘public debate’ Barrick Gold has just addressed a request to the authors of Noir Canada, asking them not to use this term anymore...).
Apart from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom to academic research and the search for truth that is fundamental to any democratic society.
