What was produced in the billing factory of Zuschlag &amp; Co.?
On October 8, the trial in the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The defendants are accused in particular of involvement in organized crime, as well as gross negligence and business fraud, and other criminal acts, including document counterfeiting.
According to the prosecutor’s office, the funds raised from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often attested by fake invoices.
State funds and subsidies from the self-government - a total of HUF 65 million - are said to have flown in part to the treasuries of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, and in part to the private treasures of individuals.
As the investigative authorities announced, fictitious invoices were submitted when collecting the tender fees, and the associations are also said to have failed to meet their obligations.
According to the prosecution, most of the bills were forged.
The bills were purchased at the market in Józsefváros, and the round seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies to issue the invoices was made on that round trip north of the Plattensee to which István Lados was sent by János Zuschlag.
In the course of this "exploration tour", Lados should explore pensions and restaurants.
He requested bills on consumption in order to be able to subsequently issue bills for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Budapest Municipality based on these templates.
These accounts are said to have been manipulated mostly by István Lados and his accomplice, András Őri, who, according to our information, was responsible for drawing up the corresponding reports.
One of the goals of Lados' "exploration tour" was a beer bar.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and Co in 2003, the catering company is said to have hosted the ninety-member group of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
Now, however, the head of the enterprise says that such a large group would not have adjusted into the premises at once.
Another invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also showed serious form and content errors.
In a guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than ten people at the same time, according to the bill, 130 guests stayed.
The imagination of the counterfeiters appears to have no limits, as was the case with Pigal Kft., a catering company in whose accounts documents of clients Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá do not appear at all, according to the prosecutor’s office.
As the managing director Győző Farkas told the hvg.hu, he was immediately aware that it was fake documents when documents were presented to him by the prosecutor’s office during an interrogation.
"Our company name and tax number were incorrectly placed on the stamp."
And further: Apart from the shape defects, the fact that the plant is said to have housed a hundred people was also wrong, after having a total of eleven rooms that were impossible to accommodate so many people.
Food was also included in the bill, with the restaurant no longer operating for a long time.
The counterfeiters also failed to verify that the Budapest travel agency they targeted only offers travel abroad, and so they indicated Hungary travel on the cash bill, which also contradicted the company’s billing practice.
As it became known during the investigation, they also indicated VAT on the invoices, although travel agency services relating to a country outside the EU are VAT-free.
In total, the amount of VAT was incorrect on four invoices issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, as the company only charged 15% of VAT instead of 25, and the employees only issued machine invoices, but the falsified documents were handwritten.
Another mistake that the “accountants” had failed to make was that in one case they had stated “goods transportation” as a rendered service, although this is not offered by the firm specializing in investment advice, the prosecutor’s office said.
Further formal errors – the incorrect format of the invoice, the incorrect stamp – were due to the fact that the invoices issued to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, as well as to XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont could be detected as counterfeit.
The same applies to Ravenna Bt. and the sporting camp Kunfehértó, whose managers claimed that they had never issued the invoices.
Another "error" is the fact that the counterfeiters at the HIB Kft. from Nyíregyháza have failed: this company was in disintegration at the time (2001) when the group of the Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have eaten there - the mass manager therefore stated that he did not issue the invoices himself.
Consciously falsified
The other group of accountants are people who were quite aware that they would have to make fictitious bills.
At the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, the Foundation Esély Budapestért Alapítvány issued accounts for the Foundation Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, amounting to approximately HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the managing director of Collab Kft. was persuaded by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue the fictitious invoices.
Biogate Kft., which is also currently in liquidation, is also alleged to have cooperated with Zuschlag and Co.: In 2003, the GmbH allegedly supplied the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, as well as the Associations Atlasz Egyesület and Vörösfenyő Egyesület with counterfeit invoices worth HUF 5 million, which were related to non-performed services.
However, there was also a lack of payment traffic, as the invoices were cancelled immediately after they were issued, which the persons concerned forgot to note in their documents.
The third group of accountants includes persons who are directly connected with the accused.
One of them is Ivan Kubatov, the messenger of the Ukrainian managing director of Delta Trió Kft., a Budapest-based fuel and vehicle trading company, but not found there.
This company is said to have issued several invoices for the sale of computer components worth approximately HUF 18 million in the period from October to December 2005.
According to the Investigative Authority, Cash Investment Kft. from Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005, is alleged to have acted as the buyer of these accounts.
The managing director of this company was a Romanian, to whom the company documents should also be delivered by Iván Kubatov, between 2002 and 2005.
According to our information, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he had issued invoices on behalf of the GmbH to the associations Atlasz and Hoppá, as well as to the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he himself had paid the equivalent.
The companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. are said to have been founded by Romanian Mauriers at Iván Kubatov’s express request.
In reality, however, none of these companies were active, which, according to the accused, was due to lack of orders.
Nevertheless, he was able to benefit from the companies: At the request of his accomplice, the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who was charged with the preparation of the company’s founding documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations associated with the procurement, such as Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
In total, Kubatov issued 15 invoices worth HUF 14.2 million on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade.
The prosecutor’s office believes that Kubatov could have collected 10% of the invoice amount and VAT.
Kubatov is even alleged to have abused the company Szi-Beri Bt. for the issuance of fictitious invoices - in this case, the invoices were matched to the applications of Biztos Pont.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted their applications to the Socialist Party’s non-profit organization Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (“TMA”) in January 2006.
Both received 500,000 forints each, but they used these amounts for nothing.
To hide this, they submitted to TMA five fictitious invoices from Works Team Kft.
These invoices, by the way, were seized during the search of the office of Árpád Kemecsei in the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some defendants are now expected to have confessed to the method of counterfeiting, as they have already been made before the public prosecutor’s office.
It could be a sensation if the main accused, János Zuschlag, decides to make a comprehensive confession.
His previous statements were, in fact, less detailed, and although he had promised several times to report extensively on everything, his confession is still pending.
The question remains, therefore, whether this is in his interest, whether the Socialists have concluded a pact with him concerning the compensation of the majority of the HUF 50 million damage incurred, and whether Subsidian is willing to take responsibility in return.
However, it is quite possible that Supplement now plays the "offended" after his requests for mitigation of detention and house arrest had struck on deaf ears.
While other criminals, who have caused far greater damage with economic crimes and have not reimbursed them, are free, or at least under house arrest, this possibility remains denied.
The Psychology of Exaggeration – or Why We Are Ready to Pay More
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and therefore overestimate the wrong bid.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now managed to discover the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the magazine "Science", people do not want to be beat in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even exaggerated prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological pattern of this “game” with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play lottery, while the other was involved in a playful action – in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, however, an increased activity of the striatum, a complex beneath the cerebral cortex, was measured in the losers of the auction, where the opponent’s overbidding plays a significant role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the nervous system’s “self-rewarding.”
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding the overreaction of the striatum.
To support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also engaged in additional research to track money.
In this case, three groups should bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they came out of the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was that one group focused on winning while the other group focused on losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to make higher bets than those in the control or "win" group.
"These findings cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
They have, in fact, justified the behaviors observed at auctions so far only with the joy of winning, or the avoidance of risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to the imaging neurological processes, so we have now prepared a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases triggered by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - hepatitis and jaundice are common, however, the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E, through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, secretions or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against the viruses A and B in any case, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from the much more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people is on medication.
Also, hepatitis C can have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups where this condition is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooers.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected with a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the general practitioner at the first signs of unknown origin.
If detected in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thus eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
World Hepatitis Day is celebrated on September 30th, 2004 and is held worldwide for the first time.
The action aims to raise awareness of this chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, its origin and the importance of early detection.
