You are what you tell about yourself
On the occasion of its 10th birthday, Google can rightly assert that it can be found in people’s pockets just as it can be found over their heads in the sky: it knows where people spent their holidays, what specialists they go to, and what moves them.
And that’s still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of Google’s chief executives.
In the direction of skeptics, who are plagued by Orwell’s horror visions, he makes the direction: They would just ignore the essence of the Web 2.0.
In an interview with the Financial Times recently, Schmidt said the main goal of Google is to collect even more personal data about users and thus get closer to the company’s original goal of “ordering all the information in this world.”
Schmidt explained that after ten years of working on changing the world, Google is still only at the beginning of gathering information.
When asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said he wished Google would be able to answer questions such as "What should I do tomorrow?" or "What job really suits me?" but software programs were not yet able to do so because they didn't know enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their internet searches the search terms, as well as the IP addresses from which it was searched, and the pages visited would be registered.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows the visitor to save his or her own search history and later access it, so that the hits can be generated much more accurately later, and on the same logic are also based the so-called "recommendations", with which the system recommends tailored products and services based on previous preferences.
Users, however, wonder what happens in the event of data abuse – “If you look at what I do” – some are concerned about Google’s data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is more the potential power represented by the company that arouses fear, and less the guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom, or the rebellion against power that encounters rejection among many Internet users.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but also passed on to third parties, and in these legal cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A recent example of this was the recent action against pedophilia in Brazil, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected from the community site called “Orkut” which also enabled the identification of pedophiles.
Users concerned about personal rights, however, could still breathe in May, when Google together with the civil rights organization EFF successfully brought the FBI to court: according to this, Google can also in the future with no point of the constitution to be forced to disclose information to the FBI on secret request.
(H, the federal government has successfully obtained the issuance of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms with reference to the Youth Protection Act passed years ago, but the list of individual users, respectively their web and search terms list, has been withheld retroactively for two months.)
So Google’s image remains controversial: Those who are reluctant to disclose their personal data because they fear the loss of their private and intimate sphere through the use of Google’s services, mock the company with the indignation due to the conservative companies.
However, the American "geek culture", which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, sees the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, unlike Microsoft, which is the market leader thanks to Windows, even though they both struggle for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that, unlike Microsoft, Google does not require any identification codes from its users and provides its services for free, so an open, constantly updated source code and program package appears to be much more attractive, youthful and cool than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, the geeks look sharply at the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet – a relationship that has been put into the spotlight especially in recent years thanks to the term “Web 2.0”.
The “Web 2.0” is nothing more than collaboration, i.e. the users deliberately leave traces and take advantage of the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions vary individually, the main thing remains the same, namely to show themselves in public.
An average teenager can manage his profile on several social media sites at the same time – from Facebook to Xanga, can connect it through other services such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and can eventually integrate all this into a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. In addition, they can maintain blogs that automatically represent the latest photo galleries geostated on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other exemplary cases prove: When looking at last night’s party photos, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful friend was having fun with, or the employee is fired because he is just too honestly airing his anger about the company’s management on his blog – one thing is certain: The term “privacy” has now been completely reinterpreted.
Who leads an online life is what he reveals about himself – in this way, you could formulate the basic idea behind the behavior of today’s youth.
And anyone who tries to keep something secret, or even bypass Google’s monopoly, can do so with pleasure – like with Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google’s search engine but deliberately leaves no traces.
