Intelligent car imitates the flight of the hummel
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents, if not to mimic the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, a stunning project was presented that inspired Nissan engineers from Hummeln to create new accident-preventing systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the automotive-robot-controlled BR23C biomimetic system, a mini-car equipped with the properties of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval “private area” that is very similar to our own “protective shield,” Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at a angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers resorted to the idea of a laser-controlled distance meter.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-prevention process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of seconds, and the auto robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires at the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctive.
“If it wasn’t, the auto robot’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield – a layer within which accidents are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they avoid other bees.
This has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, the evasion, unlike the bees, can not take place up, down, or even diagonally – it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the tire’s agility.
While the bees here have endless possibilities to avoid other bees, the researchers in the auto robot could only use the rotational movement, respectively accelerating and slowing down.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter, more energy-efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond accordingly.
It does not have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical response using previous manoeuvres, so that it continuously uses only a handful of KB Memory.
No gigabyte or megabyte memory is required.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision prevention technology, which Nissan estimates will be in series production within the next ten years.
Another application could be to find the technology in GPS satellite navigation, by consciously guiding the driver around obstacles and thereby leading him to the destination.
