MP3 player accused of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as MP3 players, can lead to permanent hearing loss.
This is by the European Commission, which in a report published today in Brussels quotes the opinion of the Csrseri (Scientific Committee on Current and Recently Identified Health Risks) of the EU.
“The report shows that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music for more than one hour per day with portable music devices for at least five years are at risk of permanent hearing loss.”
“I’m worried that such a large number of teenagers who normally put portable music devices and phones at a high volume will irreversibly damage their hearing without knowing it,” said Meglena Kuneva.
“The scientific findings – as the EU says – show a clear risk that urges quick action.
What really matters is to raise consumer awareness and make this information commonplace.
In view of these scientific findings, we need to re-examine the existing control systems to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology.”
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music devices among young people.
“The scientists confirm that there is a rightful concern and that the European Commission, together with the other EU member states and stakeholders, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise that comes from portable music devices and similar devices.”
There is already a European standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100 dB.
This damage can be very limited by resorting to solutions such as reducing the volume and the length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the Scientific Committee of the EU points out that if users of portable music devices listen only five hours a week to loud (more than 89 decibels) music, then the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who exceed this limit risk complete hearing loss within five years.
That is 5-10% of the users of such devices, the number of which can be estimated to be between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
