The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already revealed itself a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion White House savings plan: A large proportion of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s issue of the New York Times, which reports how the crisis progressively divides the Republican Party, which is increasingly dividing into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favoured state institutions and the business community, and those neo-Conservatives who are hostile to “those in Washington” and the financial world, winning voters in the south and the center of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
This example, however, is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake is announcing or even already representing: not only in the U.S., but throughout the West, and beyond, will be affected by them.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long feared events, which finally take shape and come to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means a decline in the banking and financial institutions, which have close ties to abroad and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the assets of private households living in a single state.
This means an immediate political problem for governments: namely, how to behave to the affected families, which are also a huge electorate.
Economically, the crisis appears to be global, but politically, it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have fallen apart by itself and lost its right of speech: the clear evidence for this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into various national and international conflicts, does not know how to find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis has become more and more serious, only the United States is in an economic situation to save itself without foreign aid.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two non-exaggerating conditions – under certain circumstances – to which otherwise no international organization or market will be able to resort in a similar way.
That new emphasis placed on the state-national element, by the way, is in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now, when we were so convinced that we have long since entered a networked whole range, a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of the intangible, that we must suddenly see how our future will depend more and more on the essentially material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can all be transported from one place to another in the world, but they are still connected to an extremely tightly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who possesses such territory has an advantage over another who lives in an area without harvest, without water or free of oil reserves.
I now come to the second novelty, which requires a short postponement.
Whoever says territory, whoever says government, whoever says politics, whoever says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to manage things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of outrage over the existing leaders, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and somewhat worrisome aspect: a loss of confidence, an impatience, an image of pointlessness, a sense of distance, all of which is directed at a whole class of managers in Western countries.
In this way, it seems that it is the conviction among large parts of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose salary is presented to the majority as increasingly foreign and overwhelming.
The demand for leadership thus subterraneanly nourishes a branched but powerful movement of de-empowerment of the leading class and the traditional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of voters and in the immediate shift in the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, over the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, to the rebellion of American MPs against Bush (and the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role here).
You get the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, has more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value with regard to what is happening today in the lower social strata of the West and is further reinforced by the financial crisis and driven to overdimensionality.
In view of all this, it would be simply exaggerated to speak of a “rebellion of the masses.”
Keeping your eyes wide open is not possible.
