When the energy comes from the waves, suddenly the great ones rise.
It’s an inexhaustible source of money that covers over 70% of the planet’s surface and it’s only now that the world’s major energy companies seem to realize this.
Waves, currents, and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the oceans has been considered and studied for 70 years; not by chance these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When oil prices collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was gased out, but now environmental organizations and rising oil prices are pushing for new momentum in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be covered by energy generated by ocean waves.
This would double the amount of energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
Additionally, there are also the streams and tides.
Giants in attack.
The first company to now rely on marine energy is Enersis, which in 2005 signed a contract to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was released, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are now focusing on marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” a spokesman for a company known to the U.S. giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering the possibility of working with us.”
It is about obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that in Alaska, oil is continuing to be supplied by the United States and President Bush has just recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; even if the details are not known, observers speak of an increasing interest.
Technologies worth improving.
Experts speak of a technology that is still under development, not least because the final doubts of environmentalists have not yet been cleared.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are relatively small and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
But to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a much greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected boys.
The push of the waves, which moves the boys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floaters via pins and cylinders.
It is powered by a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is sent to the coast via underwater pipelines.
So far, there are four planned plants of this type, which are only waiting for government approval.
Verdant Power, however, is already producing electricity for a supermarket and a parking lot using underwater turbines in New York’s East River.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which through the resulting rotational movement feeds the generator.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tide.
According to the Institute for Electricity Extraction Research, the potential in the tides is currently of particular interest.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, sunlight and waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is the tide energy that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states to already invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
